segments.text: And I really don't think there should be any classes that size.
I could see it maybe having a very distinguished lecture and then having a whole bunch of teaching assistants take them into separate sections, but that's not the way it happens there.
They're in a class of 500, and then they have stand-time tests.
And I don't think this is fair.
More money needs to go into faculty.
and less in the building.
I think we spend all our money on the building.
And I was very glad to see a couple of years ago, if it wasn't last year, that somebody decided simply that the money was here with the faculty.
It would not go anywhere else.
I want to see more emphasis placed on teaching as something to be evaluated and .
I want to see fewer committees and less committee work because I think the people now in the community club and anywhere that's so involved in committee work, they don't have time to do that.
I'd like to see sabbaticals.
given more regularly and without complications.
And that doesn't seem to face that somebody who's done a good job for X number of years deserves it for that.
Things that would affect the whole institution.
How about the enrollment?
Yeah, I was just going to raise that issue.
And admission.
I think that they should cap the enrollment.
They already have that, don't they?
I think they have.
They say they have.
Raise the admission requirements.
And encourage or discourage out-of-state enrollment with the students.
We're not going to have dozens, well dozens of course, we're not going to have thousands and thousands of people walking in if we do that.
We make it a little more open to people from Pennsylvania and California.
I think too that we should work with junior college systems to alleviate some of the
some of that.
I know that we work with Glenn to alleviate the pressure on freshman English and technical writing.
What is your finding so far about the quality of instruction Glenn is giving?
Well, on the basic level, it's pretty much the same.
They're all our graduate students who are teaching here who are also teaching there.
Who then, in some cases, graduated
their masters and go teach there full-time, often because they're married to somebody here.
I don't think there's any problem with that.
They have worse students.
They've got some awful students over there.
And sometimes the awful students will get through the courses just because anybody who does all the work over there is going to get through.
Nobody's going to fail except people who disappear at midterm.
So we do get some people from Blinn that have high grades that aren't very
But I don't think that they're getting bad courses over there.
I think they're getting good courses.
And, in fact, I think they're getting essentially our courses.
How do you feel?
What is your thought about it in the future?
Is it optimistic, pessimistic?
Well, it's optimistic.
But I do think that we have to cap enrollment if we haven't already done it and really should reduce it somewhat.
It should go down to, oh, I'd say no more than 35.
I don't know how to do this.
This is not, but it would seem to be possible to do it.
I think a lot of it is, a lot of it is meaningless.
I read a lot of that document, and I thought that some of it is very good, but a lot of it is very vague, too.
I mean, we really need to have more instructors on all levels.
And we need to have, to be competitive with you too, we need to have a lot more instructors.
And that's in the report, but it's not specific enough.
I'm using the word instructor meaning anyone who could.
But I don't think that we can do it with, for a while we had many, many lectures.
I don't think this is a good idea because people who are really good,
instructors don't generally want to do lifetime lectures.
And we have a couple of lifetime lectures who are excellent.
But we've had many, many people pass through here, some of whom were terrible.
So I think we need more tenure track people.
And those lectures we do have, we need to treat well.
And we need to make them senior lecturers so that somebody, for instance, like Dorothy Van Ryber.
Have you spoken with her?
No, I've done Paul.
I haven't done Doris.
Yeah, okay.
Well, she's a lifetime lecturer.
And she will tell you what this does.
Because she's teaching essential classes.
And yet I think that there's a kind of bitterness on the part of lifetime lecturers because they're not, and she is a senior lecturer, but we need to have better conditions for our lecturers.
All right.
Any female-related experiences, plus and minus, that you want to share that we haven't already done throughout all the years?
Female-related?
Yeah.
Okay.
Being a woman faculty member, the pluses or the minuses here?
Well, I can think of lots of little slights from the old days, but nothing major.
What about a positive where you say, okay, the thing has turned.
The tide is going the positive way.
Being a female, I don't know.
I do remember that when I was having children, my students did not approve of this.
And one of them said to me, this is a negative experience, a core person said to me, I wouldn't let my wife be pregnant and teach.
Here I was about eight months pregnant and I was teaching her.
And I don't remember what I said to him.
I remember I looked at him in astonishment, but I don't remember, I don't think I had any snappy comeback.
I think I just said, well, that's lovely for you, and went on to something else.

I encountered that quite a bit and it was kind of funny because there were a bunch of pregnant teachers in the English department at once Pat Harris was in the department then and she was pregnant and there was a woman named Judy Finn who hasn't been around for years and years and she was there and we kind of took up the whole faculty room but there was a certain amount of you shouldn't be here at that point that was not accepted I can't think of any really awful
I never encountered and nor can I think of anything astoundingly wonderful that happened to me here because I was a woman.
I've just always been here and I've always taught and I've become aware of the improvement of attitudes towards women.
And as the years go by, there are more and more women.
There's less and less discrimination against them.
But there are still some Aggies who think the other way.
If we could get all of the people from your A&M experience into one place, to which ones and for what would you most want to express your appreciation?
Okay, Stanley Archer.
Because he guided me all these years.
He was one of the first people to recognize me as a faculty member, as opposed to another one of the teaching assistants, Frank Pierce.
Because actually, Frank was very protective during those years.
And he was one of the people that, for instance,
Back then, you didn't have any choice about where and when you taught ordinarily.
And they could just as soon send you a mile away.
But Frank Pierce was always, like when I was having children and so forth, he always made sure my classes were relatively local and that they were at good hours.
And he also, he was the first person to say, I called all these people doctor this and that.
And Frank was the first person to say, call me Frank.
And I appreciated that.
Okay, Stanley Frank, Bedford Clark, but just he's my long-term friend here.
I was here when they hired him.
I think he was a great hire.
He's always been around for good advice.
Who else?
Don't have to be in the department now.
No, they don't have to be in the department.
Anyone associated with A&M that you...
Okay, Maxine Davenport, Manuel's first wife, and Manuel himself.
Sylvia Greider, who also came in a long time ago and who has not contributed well by the system she's in.
His name comes to mind always when I think of people not being seen well.
An odd name that you may not even remember.
Do you remember Pat Hunter?
He taught everybody much food, but he was very kind to me and very helpful.
He made all kinds of dreadful mistakes with other people.
And he was best known for dragging in people to see the apartment had he let their class go by himself.
He was not winning any friends at all.
I was careful not to do that when my class was anywhere in the vicinity of parks.
But he was very good to me.
And so I would remember him.
I would go to him for advice still.
You know, when I think, except for Sylvia, these are all men.
Catherine O'Keeffe is not here anymore.
And I think that's about the list that people go to for advice.
Well, let's finish the questions and then we'll think.
I would want it for the establishment of an MFA program.
A million dollars wouldn't go far in that direction.
If I couldn't do that, then I wouldn't have speaker series, another instructor, whatever, in the area doing writing.
It's been so long.
I've been here since 1968.
I've been teaching here since 1959.
I taught elsewhere before and for one year during the country.
But other than that, I know nothing.
I don't know how the institution works.
And I certainly enjoy teaching.
And I'm feeling
But other people from that time period.
And now I'm beginning to see I've had the children of my first students.
I figure when the grandchildren show up, it's probably going to be .
And so I would say in many ways I do identify with a lot.
But I'm not.
I'm just trying to think of things.
